<subSubSection id="5FF3FA4A4082446919D4F29947C0F246" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="BE946DA64A494F6C791C679FEC536199" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C894237EA16BA10358ABF8831A4F4F8B" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">
<bibRefCitation id="179D38F9E7C4CCECEC6A8B7DAC47D79E" author="Verity, R" journalOrPublisher="Entomologist's Record" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" refId="B98" refString="Verity, R, 1920. Seasonal Polymorphism and Races of Some European Grypocera and Rhopalocera. Additional Notes. Entomologist's Record 32: 3-8, 140-152." title="Seasonal Polymorphism and Races of Some European Grypocera and Rhopalocera. Additional Notes. Entomologist's Record 32: 3 - 8, 140 - 152." year="1920">Verity (1920)</bibRefCitation>
proposed this name as a 
<normalizedToken id="21AEDA8CC3D91B677B83AD62E75C5CFB" originalValue="“race”">&quot;race&quot;</normalizedToken>
of 
<taxonomicName id="A5F22E52B94CCB617917AD2E78C5EECD" genus="H." lsidName="H. foulquieri" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" rank="species" species="foulquieri">
<emphasis id="A4FCF4DE23E91CB91583A8C047D9C07E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">H. foulquieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="CC694FF0E2D489C89F04836B5D79B41C" originalValue="Oberthür">Oberthuer</normalizedToken>
, 1910. As it was given in trinomy and the content of the description clearly indicates that a geographical race was meant, this name is available as subspecific (article 45.6 
<bibRefCitation id="550020761376F194FD36DAAC1D8E9512" author="ICZN" journalOrPublisher="Internationale Entomologische Zeitschrift" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" publicationUrl="http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" refId="B47" refString="ICZN, 1999. International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. London. [available online at http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" title="International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. London. [available online at" url="http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
). The year on the specimen labels (1937) indicate specimens were collected 17 years after description (1920) from the same location the original holotype material was collected. As a result, the black label of the specimens treated as 
<normalizedToken id="86236FF05C7F63D2B337A3E74FC5C8C2" originalValue="“types”">&quot;types&quot;</normalizedToken>
is erroneous. The specimen collected from the same geographical location from which the type specimen was collected is called topotype. According to ICZN (1999), a topotype has no formal standing and is not regulated by the Code. Therefore, these four specimens are erroneously labelled as types, should be annotated as &quot;Not a Type&quot; and are treated here as 
<normalizedToken id="81BEF252BB34D72B90EDB0D7270F2CF7" originalValue="“Non-type”">&quot;Non-type&quot;</normalizedToken>
specimens.
</paragraph>
